{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511563"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:43:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:43:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11759"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11759"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.02,0.03,0.39,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116319"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4372"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98315"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1223"},{"type":"tags","id":"1353"},{"type":"tags","id":"1627"},{"type":"tags","id":"2371"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12227"},{"type":"tags","id":"12926"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6220"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45865"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49523"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116319"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of difficulty conceiving with her long-term partner. She reports that her periods have been irregular for the past two years, sometimes occurring up to eight weeks apart. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 28 kg/m\u00b2. She has increased facial hair, moderate-severe facial acne, and hyperpigmentation in the skin folds of her neck. Recent blood tests show thyroid stimulating hormone 2.1 mIU/L (0.4-4.0), prolactin 12 \u03bcg/L (2-25), 17-hydroxyprogesterone 1.8 nmol/L (\u0026lt;6), follicle-stimulating hormone 5.2 IU/L (follicular phase 3.5-12.5), and HbA1c 38 mmol/mol (\u0026lt;42).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most appropriate to confirm the diagnosis of polycystic ovary syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound of the ovaries","Fasting oral glucose tolerance test","Anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone level","No investigations are required","Total and free testosterone levels"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPolycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) is diagnosed using the Rotterdam criteria, which requires two out of three of the following: oligo/anovulation, clinical or biochemical hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovarian morphology. Before making the diagnosis, other causes of hyperandrogenism and menstrual irregularity should be excluded, which has been done in this case with normal thyroid, prolactin, and 17-hydroxyprogesterone levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has clinical evidence of hyperandrogenism (facial hair, acne, acanthosis nigricans) and oligomenorrhoea (irregular periods up to eight weeks apart). As per the Rotterdam criteria, these two clinical features are sufficient to make a diagnosis of PCOS. \u003Cstrong\u003ENo investigations are required\u003C/strong\u003E to confirm this diagnosis when two criteria are already met and other causes have been excluded. However, further testing relating to the patient\u0027s fertility will likely be done considering she is attempting to conceive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the ovaries\u003C/strong\u003E would only be required if the patient demonstrated only one of the Rotterdam criteria (either hyperandrogenism or oligo/anovulation). Because both are present, the criteria for PCOS are fulfilled and a diagnosis can be made without ultrasound. However, an ultrasound may be performed to identify the specific phenotype in this patient or as part of fertility investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasting oral glucose tolerance test\u003C/strong\u003E is not needed to diagnose PCOS. Metabolic syndrome and insulin dysregulation commonly occur in individuals with PCOS, and screening for diabetes is recommended in PCOS patients (especially with BMI \u0026gt;25), but an oral glucose tolerance test would not be used to confirm a diagnosis of PCOS itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-M\u00fcllerian hormone level\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary for diagnosing PCOS in this case. According to current guidelines, serum AMH can be used as an alternative to ultrasound to define polycystic ovarian morphology (PCOM) in adults when ultrasound is not available or acceptable. This makes AMH a useful tool in the diagnostic algorithm, particularly when assessing the third Rotterdam criterion. However, in patients who already have irregular menstrual cycles and hyperandrogenism (as in this case), an AMH level is not necessary for PCOS diagnosis as two criteria are already fulfilled. AMH should not be used as a single test for PCOS diagnosis and should not yet be used in adolescents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal and free testosterone levels\u003C/strong\u003E are not necessary when there is clear clinical evidence of hyperandrogenism as in this case. Biochemical evidence of hyperandrogenism can support the diagnosis when clinical signs are subtle or absent, but when hirsutism, acne, and acanthosis nigricans are present, testosterone measurement is not required to fulfill the diagnostic criteria of PCOS.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Rotterdam criteria are used to diagnose Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS), requiring 2 out of 3 criteria: oligo/anovulation, clinical/biochemical hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovaries on ultrasound.","Clinical hyperandrogenism (hirsutism, acne) and oligo/anovulation are sufficient to diagnose PCOS without additional testing when other causes are excluded.","Anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone (AMH) can be used as an alternative to ultrasound to define polycystic ovarian morphology in adults, but is not necessary when two Rotterdam criteria are already met."],"references":["Monash Centre for Health Research and Implementation. PCOS practice tools for health practitioners [Internet]. Clayton (VIC): Monash University; [cited 2025 Aug 24]. Available from: https://mchri.org.au/guidelines-resources/health-professionals/pcos-practice-tools/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98315"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11759"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98315"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T13:22:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T13:22:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4372"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116319"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t